1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,109
Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudasa Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudasa Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudasa

2
00:00:29,089 --> 00:00:57,240
homage to the blessed noble and fully self-enlightened one so I thought to say something about right livelihood this evening and then if there's time to answer one or two of these questions so when the Buddha formulated his teaching it didn't sort of come immediately it was something that grew as he taught you know

3
00:00:58,570 --> 00:01:02,496
He ended up with these, the path, the Eightfold Path.

4
00:01:02,515 --> 00:01:05,359
And that's part of this, of the Four Noble Truths.

5
00:01:06,221 --> 00:01:10,507
So the First Noble Truth simply states, states that there is dukkha.

6
00:01:10,527 --> 00:01:16,275
And dukkha translates as a hard place.

7
00:01:16,254 --> 00:01:21,682
We're in a hard place, that's what it means.

8
00:01:21,822 --> 00:01:45,992
And he defined that as being because it was in a constant state of change, then there was this ordinary suffering that we get through our unfulfilled desires and so on, and then there's that more subtle suffering of knowing that the self is not real.

9
00:01:48,655 --> 00:01:59,605
There's an underlying feeling, I think, about life because of death, because it's not steady, because it's always there in the background.

10
00:02:00,625 --> 00:02:08,532
The sense of self doesn't have a ground and that causes a deep anxiety within us.

11
00:02:10,533 --> 00:02:18,561
Indeed, you can say that all anxiety and all fear is the fear of death, fear of disappearance.

12
00:02:20,497 --> 00:02:27,250
And then he goes on to be a bit more specific and he says that the cause of suffering is this desire.

13
00:02:28,012 --> 00:02:38,210
And he simply points to that as a kernel psychological position that we have, seeking happiness in things that are simply not going to deliver, that's all.

14
00:02:38,610 --> 00:02:41,376
You wouldn't invest in a stock anymore.

15
00:02:41,355 --> 00:02:44,681
which was told to you by everybody that it would fail.

16
00:02:46,425 --> 00:02:48,530
So life will fail us.

17
00:02:48,889 --> 00:02:49,731
We're going to die.

18
00:02:49,792 --> 00:02:56,664
And yet there we are, investing everything in it.

19
00:02:57,302 --> 00:03:17,576
That desire is a psychological point and from that he then goes on to give us the wheel of dependent origination which is a template, a template of all sentient beings, that's what he says, not just human beings, which is definitely common to all human beings as to how we cause suffering for ourselves.

20
00:03:17,698 --> 00:03:20,862
That's the basic psychology that he's into.

21
00:03:20,842 --> 00:03:24,049
It's not developmental psychology.

22
00:03:24,711 --> 00:03:35,151
I mean, there is a little bit about the psychology of perception, but he's very clear, sort of one-pointed, always centering on this problem of dukkha.

23
00:03:36,233 --> 00:03:38,998
And therefore, the whole psychology is centered on that.

24
00:03:39,901 --> 00:03:42,665
And in that Second Noble Truth, he says,

25
00:03:43,641 --> 00:03:47,506
He pinpoints where the problem lies, psychologically.

26
00:03:48,467 --> 00:03:53,270
And then the third one, of course, he states quite categorically that there is an end to dukkha.

27
00:03:54,211 --> 00:03:55,693
He doesn't use the word nibbana, you see.

28
00:03:55,794 --> 00:03:57,215
Nibbana is in other texts.

29
00:03:57,716 --> 00:04:04,442
But in terms of the formulation of the Four Noble Truths, the Third Noble Truth is there is an end to dukkha, dukkha nirodha.

30
00:04:06,403 --> 00:04:10,627
And then finally, of course, he states the path leading out of it.

31
00:04:11,215 --> 00:04:20,305
And the formulation of the Four Noble Truths simply follows the way that doctors wrote their, or at least worked with an illness.

32
00:04:20,384 --> 00:04:26,471
First it was diagnosed, like Bilka, and the cause of the illness was discovered.

33
00:04:27,293 --> 00:04:32,278
And then finally the prognosis, which in this case is perfect health and happiness.

34
00:04:32,819 --> 00:04:34,982
Not health, perfect happiness.

35
00:04:35,002 --> 00:04:37,103
And the fourth was the actual medicine to be used.

36
00:04:37,124 --> 00:04:40,327
So the medicine that we're using is the Eight Four Noble Paths.

37
00:04:41,033 --> 00:04:49,781
And we begin, through this practice of meditation, with trying to correct this samādhiti, this right understanding, to see the world in a correct way.

38
00:04:50,862 --> 00:04:59,149
And when we do that, it has a systemic change, which doesn't mean to say that we can't work on these other parts of the path.

39
00:04:59,829 --> 00:05:04,935
So the second part, of course, is getting the attitude right, getting the right attitude to things.

40
00:05:04,954 --> 00:05:10,500
So today, for instance, we've been trying to develop a much clearer attitude around food.

41
00:05:10,733 --> 00:05:11,857
Why are we eating?

42
00:05:11,976 --> 00:05:15,329
You sit there and say, no, the pleasure is secondary.

43
00:05:15,490 --> 00:05:17,596
It comes up, but I'm not eating for that purpose.

44
00:05:17,656 --> 00:05:21,250
I'm eating specifically for nourishment of the body.

45
00:05:23,338 --> 00:05:32,451
And then, having got the intelligence right and the heart right, you see, got the mind and the heart right, there is that natural flow into action.

46
00:05:33,411 --> 00:05:37,677
So it's through speech, through action, right action, and then right livelihood.

47
00:05:38,458 --> 00:05:47,550
And interestingly enough, there's really no need logically to put right livelihood in there because it's included in right action.

48
00:05:47,769 --> 00:05:48,992
Livelihood is an action.

49
00:05:49,562 --> 00:05:53,682
but he obviously felt it to be so important as to have its own particular category.

50
00:05:56,696 --> 00:05:57,699
And there's

51
00:05:59,586 --> 00:06:21,108
There's an interesting passage which relates to this, where Ananda, who was his companion for the last 20-odd years of his life, comes to one of these conclusions, where he seems to always get it wrong, and one of these conclusions was that good companionship was half the spiritual livelihood, meaning the spiritual life as such.

52
00:06:22,009 --> 00:06:25,593
And the Buddha says, oh no, Ananda, it's the whole of the spiritual life.

53
00:06:26,401 --> 00:06:32,711
So that's how important our companions are, the people whom we mix with, because, of course, they affect us.

54
00:06:33,232 --> 00:06:35,035
We're in constant conversation with them.

55
00:06:35,055 --> 00:06:38,721
We relate to people who are close to us, work with us, etc., etc.

56
00:06:40,062 --> 00:06:45,833
So then he states this right livelihood as a section on its own.

57
00:06:46,012 --> 00:06:52,863
So it's worth sort of just thinking about it a little bit, reflecting on it, and seeing what sort of pointers we can get.

58
00:06:52,843 --> 00:07:07,600
The fact of the matter is that livelihood takes up so much of our life, generally speaking, that obviously it has to become a vehicle through which we can practice and hopefully liberate ourselves.

59
00:07:09,543 --> 00:07:15,509
So, just very quickly, we can dismiss all those things that are not like livelihood,

60
00:07:16,654 --> 00:07:18,661
Anything that brings harm to other people, you see.

61
00:07:19,463 --> 00:07:29,891
Trading in arms, in living beings, intoxicating drinks, poison, slaughtering, fishing, fishing, soldiering, deceit, treachery, soothsaying, trickery, usury, etc.

62
00:07:30,653 --> 00:07:31,677
See, so...

63
00:07:31,656 --> 00:07:38,613
There's a whole load of things which would not be considered skillful because they are inherently doing other people harm.

64
00:07:39,134 --> 00:07:47,877
So remember that, that all ethics, the whole of the ethical life in the Buddhist teaching simply comes down to doing harm.

65
00:07:47,857 --> 00:07:55,427
to do harm to somebody else in any way is considered to be unwholesome.

66
00:07:55,447 --> 00:08:07,884
So any job that you can see is actually doing harm to another person, or we can extend it these days to the planet, may give you cause for concern.

67
00:08:07,903 --> 00:08:11,569
I hope I've not made anybody redundant.

68
00:08:14,958 --> 00:08:29,937
Just on that note, if, of course, one finds oneself in a job which the person has ethical problems around, then you have to be kind to yourself.

69
00:08:29,956 --> 00:08:31,418
You can't just drop it there and then.

70
00:08:32,039 --> 00:08:41,150
But just by deciding that you don't want to do this job anymore and inclining towards another job, then you'll slowly find your way out of it.

71
00:08:41,130 --> 00:08:50,655
There are other conditions to be taken into consideration, generally speaking.

72
00:08:50,937 --> 00:08:57,013
For instance, I know somebody who was in the beer trade, sold beer for a company.

73
00:08:56,993 --> 00:09:05,764
And, you know, once he became into the Dharma, then he had this problem about, you know, he shouldn't be selling beer, you see.

74
00:09:07,466 --> 00:09:15,115
I never quite got a straight answer from him as to how he finally rationalized himself into keeping the job.

75
00:09:16,097 --> 00:09:18,039
But the fact was...

76
00:09:18,019 --> 00:09:23,110
But the fact was that he wanted to know what I felt.

77
00:09:23,169 --> 00:09:33,250
I said, well, if I really felt strongly about that, I would move towards another job of some sort, but I'd have to take into consideration the effects on my family.

78
00:09:33,932 --> 00:09:35,134
So I don't want to...

79
00:09:35,114 --> 00:09:44,725
take a hard position on something and then find myself being redundant and putting a huge pressure.

80
00:09:44,745 --> 00:09:49,731
I know somebody else, you see, who was in the police and had similar problems.

81
00:09:49,871 --> 00:09:51,835
He really didn't like the way the police worked.

82
00:09:51,875 --> 00:09:57,881
He got a lot of ethical problems about the way the police force works.

83
00:09:57,861 --> 00:10:02,466
So he wanted to move, and he was interested in some sort of therapy, I remember.

84
00:10:02,988 --> 00:10:09,355
But he took the road of trying to get some funding for it, and eventually he couldn't get it.

85
00:10:09,956 --> 00:10:19,407
So he simply found a corner within the police force where he felt at least he wasn't joining in those parts which he felt were unethical.

86
00:10:22,250 --> 00:10:23,532
He ended up in special branch.

87
00:10:26,092 --> 00:10:28,421
Looking after politicians.

88
00:10:30,187 --> 00:10:32,474
Yeah, that's an ethical problem.

89
00:10:35,003 --> 00:10:37,149
Don't be too cynical, you understand.

90
00:10:39,003 --> 00:10:58,142
so uh leaving all that aside uh we can then uh also delineate you know those motivations which are uh not particularly i mean they're not as bad as selling human beings and that sort of stuff uh but are unwholesome they're unskillful and um and here we come to uh this whole area of

91
00:10:58,121 --> 00:11:01,149
you know, we've got this word now, haven't we, the celebs.

92
00:11:01,789 --> 00:11:04,657
So, who are these, you know, what is a celebrity?

93
00:11:04,697 --> 00:11:10,409
It's somebody who's made it either with riches, power, or...

94
00:11:11,486 --> 00:11:13,249
Rich is power or fame, isn't it?

95
00:11:13,469 --> 00:11:17,673
They've done something that makes them well-known in their own field.

96
00:11:17,754 --> 00:11:35,434
Now, you can understand if that's the aim of your life, to get rich or to get power in order to realize your aims or simply to become famous, then it puts a twist on the job you're doing, doesn't it?

97
00:11:35,455 --> 00:11:37,157
It puts a twist on the job.

98
00:11:37,136 --> 00:11:44,725
I know that we have downers on people who've made a lot of money out of their business, you know, poor old Bill Gates comes in for a hammering.

99
00:11:45,304 --> 00:12:02,182
But the interview that I saw, I mean, his interest wasn't so much in making money, but it began with a real interest in the whole idea of computers and what computers could do, you see.

100
00:12:02,163 --> 00:12:06,332
Then, of course, it's very successful and you build an empire.

101
00:12:06,754 --> 00:12:11,423
And then, of course, you're into defense and you're up against Sony and people like that.

102
00:12:12,166 --> 00:12:14,772
And the whole thing becomes slightly twisted.

103
00:12:16,355 --> 00:12:21,264
So, again, whenever we look at the... Again, it's to do with attitude, you see.

104
00:12:21,325 --> 00:12:24,150
It's not about not getting money.

105
00:12:24,932 --> 00:12:26,315
The Buddha, again, is quite clear.

106
00:12:26,414 --> 00:12:29,682
It's not how much you earn that's important.

107
00:12:30,283 --> 00:12:33,570
It's how you earn it.

108
00:12:33,854 --> 00:12:36,837
The amount you get is neither here nor there.

109
00:12:36,859 --> 00:12:38,881
And then, of course, what you do with the amount.

110
00:12:39,341 --> 00:12:41,645
What do you do with the money you have, you see?

111
00:12:42,226 --> 00:12:46,413
And if it's done for the benefit of others, then obviously it's a very wholesome thing.

112
00:12:47,053 --> 00:12:56,748
So the Buddha is definitely into entrepreneurship, and I'm sure he'd be a supporter of some form of capitalism if he was here.

113
00:12:56,768 --> 00:12:57,870
I hope nobody's going to shoot me.

114
00:12:58,778 --> 00:13:09,034
So the case is that this business of making money, if you look at somebody like Anathapindika, so he was one of his great supporters.

115
00:13:09,154 --> 00:13:16,287
Anathapindika was a merchant, made a lot of money and bought grounds for a monastery.

116
00:13:16,427 --> 00:13:22,677
In fact, so the tale goes that he wanted to buy this park from Prince Jeta.

117
00:13:22,657 --> 00:13:25,799
And the prince didn't want to sell it at all.

118
00:13:26,301 --> 00:13:32,427
So he said he would only sell it if it was completely covered with gold coins.

119
00:13:33,008 --> 00:13:41,316
So an Atapindika wanting to make this gift to the Buddha completely covered with gold coins and got it from Prince Jeta.

120
00:13:41,336 --> 00:13:44,158
And it's known as the Jetavana Monastery.

121
00:13:44,740 --> 00:13:46,601
And obviously the Buddha liked being there.

122
00:13:46,621 --> 00:13:47,802
It was a nice place.

123
00:13:48,374 --> 00:13:58,187
So, and Ars Benica then, it seems, loses all his money, and even in abject poverty, he never comes to the monastery without something.

124
00:13:58,388 --> 00:14:11,105
So at one point, he arrives just with soil in his hands that he's picked up from his own garden, good soil, and he spreads it onto the monastery grounds.

125
00:14:12,528 --> 00:14:14,870
Later, it seems, he does become...

126
00:14:15,408 --> 00:14:33,349
rich again and in the as the story goes he dies as a sort of panna so in other words he's one of the noble ones one who has intuitive nibbana you see so there's hope for us hope for us all I think even hope for the rich I wouldn't say

127
00:14:33,615 --> 00:14:39,807
So it's a case of there's nothing actually wrong with being rich.

128
00:14:40,308 --> 00:14:42,653
That's the point from the Buddha's point of view.

129
00:14:43,676 --> 00:14:45,880
And of course the same can go for power.

130
00:14:46,061 --> 00:14:53,615
I mean people who use power just for perfect selfish reasons, well we've got lots of examples

131
00:14:53,596 --> 00:14:58,604
Of those these days, it's one of the big problems, for instance, in Africa, isn't it?

132
00:14:59,063 --> 00:15:04,032
Really bad governance where people just screw their own people from all sorts of things.

133
00:15:05,052 --> 00:15:13,966
But obviously when you get somebody who is in power and has power for the benefit of the society that they're in,

134
00:15:13,947 --> 00:15:19,552
then obviously it's not something to be seen as unskillful or unwholesome.

135
00:15:20,053 --> 00:15:21,554
Somebody has to make decisions.

136
00:15:22,015 --> 00:15:24,759
Even in a small workplace, somebody has to make decisions.

137
00:15:25,460 --> 00:15:27,201
Whoever makes decisions has the power.

138
00:15:27,923 --> 00:15:37,373
So it's a case of, again, power not in itself being something unskillful or unwholesome, but basically how we use it.

139
00:15:39,091 --> 00:15:47,644
And just on a side of that, in our lives, especially, say, places at work, we all of us have, shall we say, a ring of power.

140
00:15:48,205 --> 00:15:51,490
We can all do something, affect something.

141
00:15:51,509 --> 00:15:57,879
And then there's another ring, which is about influence, so we can influence people to do things.

142
00:15:58,779 --> 00:16:00,864
And then, of course, it stops, you see.

143
00:16:01,605 --> 00:16:08,575
And a lot of our problems arise because we don't recognize where the end of that ring is.

144
00:16:08,554 --> 00:16:15,065
So when we try to exercise more power than we have, then of course we tend to become frustrated.

145
00:16:16,886 --> 00:16:34,072
And if we find ourselves not using our power but being overridden by others who are less powerful than us, then we feel that we've let people down, we've not lived up to our responsibility because with power there comes that responsibility.

146
00:16:34,052 --> 00:16:35,576
And it's the same with influence.

147
00:16:36,096 --> 00:16:41,308
Whatever influence we have, we should use for the benefit of others.

148
00:16:41,408 --> 00:16:47,261
But when we see that our influence is not working, then you have to be very careful that you accept that boundary.

149
00:16:47,702 --> 00:16:53,174
If you don't accept that boundary, then again you start feeling frustrated and all sorts of stuff.

150
00:16:53,154 --> 00:17:09,638
So people, especially in those areas which are caught up in that work where there's a lot of emotional value put on it, like ecological issues and political issues.

151
00:17:10,701 --> 00:17:17,931
And if they don't accept where their boundary of power and influence lies, then they just get burnout, and that doesn't help anybody at all.

152
00:17:19,935 --> 00:17:22,583
So that's important too, isn't it?

153
00:17:23,085 --> 00:17:33,252
To know the extent of what we're capable of doing ourselves and of how much we are capable of getting other people to do things.

154
00:17:35,359 --> 00:17:36,542
And then fame.

155
00:17:36,682 --> 00:17:40,951
Fame is probably the shallowest of them all, really.

156
00:17:41,051 --> 00:17:49,028
But as you know, famous people, either film stars or football stars and whatnot, you can use it for the benefit of others.

157
00:17:49,309 --> 00:17:53,939
I suppose a very good example of that is Bob Geldof, isn't it?

158
00:17:54,019 --> 00:17:55,663
After all, he's only a musician.

159
00:17:55,643 --> 00:17:58,386
And yet he's able to motivate, isn't he?

160
00:17:58,406 --> 00:17:59,568
He's able to motivate people.

161
00:18:00,470 --> 00:18:11,365
And so anything that we have, even within our small area of influence, which is done for the benefit of others, is thereby wholesome.

162
00:18:11,707 --> 00:18:19,238
I mean, if one becomes famous and then one gets a very big head, then it just becomes a headache in the end, doesn't it?

163
00:18:20,990 --> 00:18:27,479
And all these things, all these things, of course, when they're taken from you, they cause misery.

164
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:28,980
They cause a lot of misery.

165
00:18:29,961 --> 00:18:41,298
I always remember that case of a very young immigrant to, an East European immigrant, I can't remember his name now, to Australia, who in a very short length of time built up this huge property empire.

166
00:18:42,199 --> 00:18:47,165
And when property dropped in, I think it was in the 80s, wasn't it, 80s, 90s, he committed suicide.

167
00:18:49,221 --> 00:19:03,627
So you can see how we can make this mistake of actually identifying with the power we have, no matter how little it is, and the riches, and the fame.

168
00:19:04,990 --> 00:19:08,596
And that's one of the big problems with being made redundant, isn't it?

169
00:19:08,576 --> 00:19:23,239
I mean, being made redundant in our society, sure, it's a catastrophe in a sense that your wage can go, your sense of work can go, all that sort of stuff.

170
00:19:23,859 --> 00:19:31,951
But what turns people, what makes it despairing, of course, is that relationship that the person had with the job.

171
00:19:31,932 --> 00:19:41,079
You lose your sense of identity because unwittingly you define yourself by the work you do, don't you?

172
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:42,103
Whether you like it or not.

173
00:19:42,423 --> 00:19:45,232
If anybody says, what are you?

174
00:19:46,494 --> 00:19:47,276
What do you do?

175
00:19:47,296 --> 00:19:49,880
You don't say, well, I clean the toilet at home.

176
00:19:50,882 --> 00:19:52,625
You say, well, I teach.

177
00:19:52,865 --> 00:19:54,307
You don't say, I cook a meal every so often.

178
00:19:54,326 --> 00:19:55,148
You say, what do you do?

179
00:19:55,789 --> 00:20:00,696
Even our crucial questions always point to, actually, what do you do in society?

180
00:20:01,317 --> 00:20:08,148
And from what you do in society, we tend to build up our self-esteem, our self-importance.

181
00:20:08,128 --> 00:20:09,772
All those sorts of areas.

182
00:20:10,094 --> 00:20:11,517
And of course our basic wealth.

183
00:20:12,038 --> 00:20:22,602
So when these are taken from us in an act of redundancy, that's when you hit that despair because you have to redefine yourself.

184
00:20:22,622 --> 00:20:27,353
And the definition of being unemployed isn't a particularly happy one in our society.

185
00:20:27,973 --> 00:20:32,338
So it's really just being aware of that, being aware of that.

186
00:20:32,779 --> 00:20:47,377
And if things happen to us which take away our wealth and power and good name, fame doesn't here just mean famous in the sense of pop stars, it just means your good name.

187
00:20:47,518 --> 00:20:50,521
So somebody can take away your good name, you see.

188
00:20:50,501 --> 00:21:05,862
And to do that you have to watch that and watch your reaction to it if that happens to you and recognize that the suffering you're getting from it is the measure of your attachment to the wealth you had and the power you had and the good name you had, you see.

189
00:21:08,035 --> 00:21:10,218
And in that way, you don't justify it.

190
00:21:10,438 --> 00:21:12,500
This is the problem with these negative emotions.

191
00:21:12,902 --> 00:21:14,022
We actually justify them.

192
00:21:14,042 --> 00:21:15,384
We say we ought to be angry.

193
00:21:15,746 --> 00:21:16,886
We ought to be depressed.

194
00:21:17,027 --> 00:21:18,910
We ought to be fearful.

195
00:21:19,451 --> 00:21:21,933
And as soon as you do that, you empower these states.

196
00:21:22,474 --> 00:21:34,332
So whenever something like that happens, you have to really back off and sit in your meditation and recognize that these are actually all measures of some form of attachment, some form of wrong view.

197
00:21:35,192 --> 00:21:35,393
That's it.

198
00:21:38,578 --> 00:21:50,157
So even if we look at various jobs, I mean, most people can find some sort of compassionate angle to what they do.

199
00:21:50,459 --> 00:22:13,732
I mean, it's easy in sort of areas of service, areas, you know, health workers, people like that, teaching profession, doctors, all that sort of area is really, and even the police, for heaven's sake, all that sort of area is, I would have thought, fairly easy to develop a right attitude.

200
00:22:13,712 --> 00:22:19,202
to see the job as something that is being done for others, a sense of service.

201
00:22:22,327 --> 00:22:38,016
When it comes to other jobs such as even entrepreneurship, business work and all that, you often get a bit of a downer on that, making money, setting up a business and all that.

202
00:22:38,451 --> 00:22:41,221
But actually, it's another service, isn't it?

203
00:22:41,644 --> 00:22:49,692
And depending on your attitude, depending on the purpose of what you're doing, then it can be tremendously worthwhile, wholesome.

204
00:22:51,782 --> 00:23:04,921
Now when it comes to even those jobs that at one point we used to use the word workers, now it's more politically correct to talk about operatives.

205
00:23:04,941 --> 00:23:11,529
So when you're a machine operative and you're doing something very repetitive, very monotonous,

206
00:23:11,509 --> 00:23:38,125
then I think that, you know, I mean, there's also that, you can engender that sense of it being a service, you know, like somebody has to do the job, I mean, that's a bit of a negative way of looking at it, but in the sense that whatever the product is, so long as it's a wholesome product, a good product, you know, then this is what the society's offered you at this particular point, and one does what one can within that situation.

207
00:23:39,454 --> 00:23:51,290
Now, there are some jobs which, shall we say, are more directly effective upon the heart.

208
00:23:51,571 --> 00:24:07,133
I mean, to work with the sick, with the dying and all that, immediately, especially working with people, has an immediate effect with right attitude of extending the heart, of making it grow in those areas that we call the limitables, you know.

209
00:24:07,113 --> 00:24:09,797
because they can be developed indefinitely.

210
00:24:09,957 --> 00:24:16,247
So love, compassion, sympathetic joy, care, all those lovely attitudes can be developed.

211
00:24:17,608 --> 00:24:32,833
But when you get into a job where you're working with a machine, say in an office or in a factory, then of course it's difficult to have the same value of compassion towards a machine and whatnot.

212
00:24:32,813 --> 00:24:40,227
But there is an opportunity there to see it as a meditative exercise.

213
00:24:41,169 --> 00:24:53,353
And I often think about people these days even, but even more so in earlier times in our society where so many people had very repetitive jobs doing the same thing.

214
00:24:53,333 --> 00:24:55,075
And of course that's all we're doing, isn't it?

215
00:24:55,134 --> 00:24:56,057
Rising, falling.

216
00:24:56,076 --> 00:24:58,480
You couldn't get more repetitive than watching the breath, you see.

217
00:24:59,221 --> 00:25:14,480
And if you were to take that same attitude to a repetitive job, no matter what you're doing, of using it to establish this constant mindfulness, then you can see it would definitely have a strong spiritual impact.

218
00:25:14,461 --> 00:25:15,122
effort to it.

219
00:25:15,623 --> 00:25:23,298
I remember, I just, even I myself, when I was a kid, you know, used to get a job, you know, 16, 17, get a job after school.

220
00:25:24,080 --> 00:25:27,508
And one job I had was in this bakery, this cake factory.

221
00:25:29,007 --> 00:25:38,142
And there was a line of women who followed the process from when the dough arrived or whatever, when they baked.

222
00:25:38,162 --> 00:25:44,972
And they sort of swung round and went round this little machine and things were added onto this cake as it came round, you see.

223
00:25:45,413 --> 00:25:49,480
And I was given the job of adding the cherry round the top.

224
00:25:49,460 --> 00:25:51,102
It was the last point, you see.

225
00:25:51,583 --> 00:25:53,766
And as it swung round with all...

226
00:25:54,126 --> 00:25:55,749
I had to get this chair in and stick it on, you see.

227
00:25:56,630 --> 00:26:04,560
Well, occasionally, of course, I'd miss, or it wasn't centred, and I'd sort of go after it and try and put it... And eventually, you know, they shifted me.

228
00:26:04,580 --> 00:26:06,123
I was absolutely useless.

229
00:26:06,143 --> 00:26:06,663
And there was a...

230
00:26:07,525 --> 00:26:13,032
Even though I protested that I was school captain, it was dexterous of my feet, and if you'd just give me time, I could actually do this job, you know?

231
00:26:14,355 --> 00:26:19,382
And I remember these lovely, sort of kindly, simpering looks from the women, you know, oh, he's only a boy, and all that sort of stuff.

232
00:26:20,324 --> 00:26:34,890
But the thing is that just being able to accept one's position there and just to use it as a concentration exercise, you can see that even something so repetitive can be turned to spiritual advantage.

233
00:26:43,038 --> 00:26:49,929
So you might think then, well, what would be, how would you profile a good day, you know, a good day at work?

234
00:26:50,249 --> 00:26:59,124
How would you set your mind to take as much spiritual advantage out of the work that you can get, you see?

235
00:26:59,924 --> 00:27:06,935
So the first thing, of course, is to get up and do your two-hour meditation, you see?

236
00:27:06,915 --> 00:27:10,601
And then, after that, to develop a bit of loving-kindness, you see.

237
00:27:10,642 --> 00:27:28,989
Now, in that sort of loving-kindness that you're developing, to actually bring the people whom you work with to mind, to bring the place to mind, to bring everybody associated to mind, you see, and what you're doing is you're establishing a right relationship.

238
00:27:29,209 --> 00:27:31,792
So, right attitude is right relationship, you see.

239
00:27:32,396 --> 00:27:42,298
And if there's somebody whom you're having problems with, to at least offer an attitude of no harm and occasionally just think of their brighter side.

240
00:27:43,541 --> 00:27:49,494
So in a sense, you're setting yourself right with the people, with the people whom you have to work with.

241
00:27:49,555 --> 00:27:51,839
But there's also the job, you see.

242
00:27:51,819 --> 00:28:04,736
Now, I can't think of a job which doesn't have, you know, this quality of repetition to it, no matter how, I mean, everything in life has this sort of repetitive quality about it, you know.

243
00:28:05,757 --> 00:28:11,785
And we go through periods of boredom with it and periods of not wanting to do it.

244
00:28:11,805 --> 00:28:18,232
So if you get out of bed in the morning and there's just this huge desire to take a day off, you see,

245
00:28:18,212 --> 00:28:28,888
then to actually stay with that, not to be hijacked by it, no matter how much you can justify it for all sorts of reasons.

246
00:28:28,909 --> 00:28:42,869
And to let that feeling, that sort of down feeling, to just evaporate a little bit and then to make that commitment to give your best to the job in hand, you see.

247
00:28:42,849 --> 00:28:45,959
And by doing that, you see, the heart will lift.

248
00:28:46,339 --> 00:28:50,874
The heart won't lift unless you make a decision.

249
00:28:51,675 --> 00:28:56,691
Once you make a decision to do something, the heart will follow your decision.

250
00:28:58,273 --> 00:29:12,176
So it's a case of, for instance, if you want to, say, do a job, say you've got a job at work, and you want to do the job, if there's a negativity towards it, now it's the same in meditation.

251
00:29:12,758 --> 00:29:18,847
If you suppress it, then it remains there as a rumbling within the psyche.

252
00:29:18,827 --> 00:29:34,809
But if you accept that there's a negativity towards the job, right, and you're just there with it and you can distance from it, you know, with this wonderful noting technique, yeah, and it's there, you know it's there, and then you override it, you see, you override it with right attitude.

253
00:29:35,391 --> 00:29:37,073
And that lifts the heart, you see.

254
00:29:38,452 --> 00:29:49,770
On a slightly parallel situation is when you might feel angry towards a colleague or a workmate.

255
00:29:49,791 --> 00:30:02,352
So you see, these days, especially through certain therapies, not all of them, you get these things about owning your emotion.

256
00:30:02,332 --> 00:30:07,940
Now that's all right, it's just that people confuse that owning with actually being.

257
00:30:08,560 --> 00:30:12,926
So it's all right to say, you know, there is anger arising with this person.

258
00:30:13,007 --> 00:30:20,596
But as soon as you say, I am angry with this person, and then of course you have to be authentic, inverted commas, and you have to tell the person that you're angry with them.

259
00:30:20,616 --> 00:30:24,643
Now, you know, how do you feel when somebody comes up and says, I'm angry with you?

260
00:30:24,682 --> 00:30:27,006
I mean, what's your response to that, you know?

261
00:30:27,188 --> 00:30:34,034
While I was at Gaia, I had a manager who was forever coming to see me and would sit there and say, I've got problems with you.

262
00:30:35,234 --> 00:30:36,435
What am I supposed to say?

263
00:30:36,875 --> 00:30:39,077
I'd say, oh, what can I do about that?

264
00:30:39,558 --> 00:30:41,019
And she was being authentic.

265
00:30:41,039 --> 00:30:41,921
She was being truthful.

266
00:30:45,243 --> 00:30:49,887
And of course, the presumption is that I am the cause of her dissatisfaction with me.

267
00:30:50,968 --> 00:30:55,152
And when you go to work and you say, look, I'm very angry with you, what you're saying is you are the cause of my anger.

268
00:30:55,172 --> 00:30:56,232
What are you going to do about it?

269
00:30:58,086 --> 00:31:07,641
So it's recognizing that all those negative states are arising out of me because of some wrong attitude.

270
00:31:08,161 --> 00:31:17,134
Now we know from our meditation that we can't sink them, we can't push them away, try to bury them, but we can, as it were, shift them to the side.

271
00:31:17,576 --> 00:31:18,596
This is being skillful.

272
00:31:18,978 --> 00:31:26,210
So it's not me, it's not I am angry, there is anger, and I'll deal with you when the opportunity occurs.

273
00:31:26,809 --> 00:31:36,025
So it's not a case of pushing it away and suppressing it, it's simply putting it to the side, dealing with it at an appropriate time.

274
00:31:36,005 --> 00:31:40,369
And then, of course, one raises the attitude of kindness.

275
00:31:40,711 --> 00:31:42,913
See, kindly words, a smile, you see.

276
00:31:43,433 --> 00:31:48,661
And then, of course, you find your heart lifts towards that, lifts towards that attitude and supports you.

277
00:31:50,563 --> 00:31:55,388
But again, it would be a mistake to think that, therefore, I am kind, you see.

278
00:31:55,669 --> 00:32:02,518
It's just that there is now kindness and this is the relationship that I'm engendering towards this particular person.

279
00:32:04,539 --> 00:32:09,960
So getting the attitude right every morning is important.

280
00:32:10,952 --> 00:32:25,531
So now, when it comes to the work itself, to re-establish why it is you're doing this work, and give it an attitude which is worthwhile and meaningful spiritually.

281
00:32:26,173 --> 00:32:26,773
You can do that.

282
00:32:27,474 --> 00:32:36,066
Apart from these dreadful jobs that some people do, most times you can find a worthwhile reason for doing the work.

283
00:32:36,838 --> 00:33:00,113
So then one goes into the workplace and one sits at one's place or takes up the position of your workplace and just to stop for a minute and to re-establish, to constantly re-establish that sense of mindfulness, right attitude and then to give yourself to the work.

284
00:33:00,363 --> 00:33:07,835
Now, it's a case of being loose in that situation and of recognizing that we're in relationship with other people.

285
00:33:07,875 --> 00:33:09,238
This is if you're working with other people.

286
00:33:09,617 --> 00:33:11,080
You're in relationship with other people.

287
00:33:11,882 --> 00:33:14,306
So it's much the same as our meditation.

288
00:33:14,445 --> 00:33:19,114
When you're sitting here in meditation, so, okay, we've got this...

289
00:33:19,094 --> 00:33:39,094
desire to investigate what's going on inside me but if somebody comes in here now and starts talking and draws our attention if we see that as a disturbance we're immediately in conflict so we're immediately raising all those dreadful states that here we're supposed to be trying to let go of

290
00:33:39,074 --> 00:33:56,135
So it's the same at work, where you're doing work and a colleague comes and they're all flustered or whatever, and it's a case of, you know, you can say little things like, just one minute, just one minute, and you know where you are, and then you respond.

291
00:33:56,356 --> 00:33:59,039
And remember that when...

292
00:34:00,505 --> 00:34:08,940
When somebody comes to you with fluster, with anger and whatnot, it's putting your concentration on what they're saying, not how they're saying.

293
00:34:09,722 --> 00:34:24,487
If you put your concentration on how they're saying, it's very difficult to stop that reaction of, you know, that immediate reaction coming from us of anger towards anger, anger towards their, you know, dumping their anxiety on us.

294
00:34:24,467 --> 00:34:35,827
But so long as your attention is on what they're saying, then you can guard yourself from that sort of immediate reaction that arises.

295
00:34:38,422 --> 00:34:54,248
Just on that point too, when you're with somebody who is coming at you in that sort of way, one of the things you can do is image, if you're quick enough that is, or at least have the idea of the Buddha hand.

296
00:34:54,407 --> 00:34:58,715
So remember this, there's a statue called the Abhaya posture, the fearlessness.

297
00:34:58,735 --> 00:35:04,784
And this goes back to when the dastardly Devadatta tried to kill the Buddha, three times I can say.

298
00:35:05,204 --> 00:35:08,047
And the third time was this dreadful elephant whom he set loose.

299
00:35:08,588 --> 00:35:12,273
And Nalagiri, the raging bull elephant, paced down upon the Buddha.

300
00:35:12,755 --> 00:35:21,889
And the Buddha stood there, held up his hand, you see, in a sort of fearless posture, and blasted the elephant with compassion.

301
00:35:22,409 --> 00:35:26,114
And the elephant, of course, immediately stopped and adored the Buddha, you see.

302
00:35:26,094 --> 00:35:38,637
Now, whether we believe the fullness of that story, the fact of the matter is that that tells us how to deal with situations where we find negativity coming towards us.

303
00:35:39,280 --> 00:35:42,806
So it's a case of protecting ourselves, protecting ourselves, you see.

304
00:35:43,367 --> 00:35:46,052
So you don't have to receive somebody's anger.

305
00:35:46,112 --> 00:35:47,153
You don't have to accept it.

306
00:35:47,173 --> 00:35:48,677
You don't have to take it in.

307
00:35:48,657 --> 00:35:57,942
You don't have to empower it by actually reacting to it.

308
00:35:58,182 --> 00:35:59,085
This is what we do, isn't it?

309
00:35:59,186 --> 00:36:01,873
You empower anger when you react to it.

310
00:36:02,123 --> 00:36:03,664
So it's a case of, right?

311
00:36:03,684 --> 00:36:06,106
And by doing that, you protect your own heart.

312
00:36:06,447 --> 00:36:11,092
But from behind the hand, at least you're offering an attitude of no harm.

313
00:36:12,112 --> 00:36:21,161
And I personally find that very easier if I'm actually listening to what they're saying and not how they're saying.

314
00:36:22,264 --> 00:36:28,329
So in my job, of course, I get occasionally very strange people.

315
00:36:28,949 --> 00:36:30,612
And I was running...

316
00:36:31,806 --> 00:36:32,427
Nobody here.

317
00:36:33,670 --> 00:36:35,072
Nobody here at all.

318
00:36:35,092 --> 00:36:43,306
And there was this occasion over a Christmas retreat that I run at Sharpham House, which is a very beautiful place, by the way.

319
00:36:43,326 --> 00:36:46,090
It's a lovely place to have a Christmas retreat.

320
00:36:47,492 --> 00:36:54,405
And because of some mistake on the calendar, one advert said the Wednesday and another one said Tuesday.

321
00:36:54,385 --> 00:36:59,213
So this elderly lady came who had seen it was Wednesday.

322
00:36:59,693 --> 00:37:07,608
And when she came and realised that, you know, she was late and it was all... She got very, very, very angry and flustered about it.

323
00:37:07,628 --> 00:37:12,516
So I was working with a very good manager who'd been a manager at Guy House.

324
00:37:13,157 --> 00:37:17,304
And she went out of her way to, you know, she gave her back...

325
00:37:17,284 --> 00:37:21,594
a day's money, tried to make her feel at home, showed her, et cetera, et cetera.

326
00:37:22,074 --> 00:37:25,762
And when we met, she was still very, very angry about it all.

327
00:37:26,262 --> 00:37:34,500
So a huge heart of compassion embraced this elderly lady and to make her feel at home, you see.

328
00:37:34,480 --> 00:37:35,782
And explained everything.

329
00:37:35,822 --> 00:37:40,789
And then the next day, she arrived in the evening.

330
00:37:40,809 --> 00:37:43,873
So the next day, I spent some time with her and showed her around the house.

331
00:37:44,293 --> 00:37:45,514
And she was still very angry.

332
00:37:45,534 --> 00:37:51,623
And once she realized that it wasn't the retreat she wanted, she wanted a hard retreat like Zen, you see.

333
00:37:51,824 --> 00:37:56,590
And the one I was leading was more of a reflective, contemplative time.

334
00:37:56,869 --> 00:38:01,737
Just spending our time a lot in reflection.

335
00:38:01,717 --> 00:38:03,438
She was angry about that, you see.

336
00:38:04,079 --> 00:38:10,505
So I was still, you know, keeping my hand up and beaming out an amazing amount of compassion and all that sort of stuff, you know.

337
00:38:11,005 --> 00:38:15,108
And then, of course, we had on Christmas Day, we broke the silence and we had cake, you see.

338
00:38:15,728 --> 00:38:21,893
And everybody got, you know, fairly loud and all that sort of stuff in the conversation without turning off people.

339
00:38:22,675 --> 00:38:26,157
And she was sitting there by the side, you see.

340
00:38:26,679 --> 00:38:31,722
And earlier I'd seen her chatting quite well or openly with these other people, you see.

341
00:38:31,702 --> 00:38:37,657
So I just went over to her, you see, and said, oh, you know, how is everything, you see?

342
00:38:37,958 --> 00:38:39,862
And off she went, moaning and groaning.

343
00:38:39,983 --> 00:38:41,125
Well, I said, oh, for heaven's sake.

344
00:38:43,451 --> 00:38:45,795
I said, you've been giving them nothing but... You see?

345
00:38:46,838 --> 00:38:47,721
And...

346
00:38:49,135 --> 00:38:49,556
You see?

347
00:38:50,137 --> 00:38:51,940
So there, you see, I'd lost my guard, you see.

348
00:38:51,981 --> 00:38:54,365
I'd chewed into it.

349
00:38:54,485 --> 00:38:56,150
Well, of course, she didn't moan again.

350
00:38:56,489 --> 00:38:59,315
Not in front of me, anyway.

351
00:39:00,398 --> 00:39:07,233
Unfortunately, we didn't have the opportunity, because we were leaving about the next day, to make it up, really.

352
00:39:07,773 --> 00:39:09,657
But I doubt if I'll be seeing her again.

353
00:39:10,786 --> 00:39:16,431
So, now, you see, what did I do?

354
00:39:16,630 --> 00:39:18,833
Well, frankly, I found it rather funny.

355
00:39:18,853 --> 00:39:27,940
But the last thing I tend to do is to get into this big self-judgment of, you know, for God's sake, you're supposed to be a monk, you're not supposed to lose your temper.

356
00:39:29,181 --> 00:39:34,226
And, you know, I just accept that, you know, that there was a failure there.

357
00:39:34,246 --> 00:39:35,728
So one records it, you see.

358
00:39:35,807 --> 00:39:36,809
One says, ah, right, you see.

359
00:39:37,248 --> 00:39:40,692
So you've got to be on your toes, you know, because you never know where somebody's at, is it?

360
00:39:41,971 --> 00:39:54,010
So this whole business of working with people who, remember, like ourselves, are going through various ranges of emotion within one day.

361
00:39:54,030 --> 00:39:55,532
I mean, just think.

362
00:39:55,733 --> 00:40:06,931
If you were to lob the amount of mental states that arise from the time you get up and the time you fall asleep, I mean, it's just, you know, it's madness, isn't it?

363
00:40:06,911 --> 00:40:10,900
I mean, you're happy, you're sad, you're depressed, you're angry, and you're fed up and you're bored.

364
00:40:10,940 --> 00:40:12,422
I mean, it's like it's constant.

365
00:40:12,443 --> 00:40:14,367
And every so often there's a little blip of peace.

366
00:40:14,387 --> 00:40:16,250
Oh, God, you know, relaxation.

367
00:40:16,269 --> 00:40:16,791
I'm happy.

368
00:40:16,831 --> 00:40:17,652
I'm happy.

369
00:40:17,672 --> 00:40:20,719
You know, they tell the world and suddenly, oh, get angry again.

370
00:40:22,538 --> 00:40:27,844
So they sort of held us skeleton of our emotional life, you see.

371
00:40:28,023 --> 00:40:45,525
And when you actually catch that that's how I am and I expect other people to be compassionate and kind towards me and not to get angry and to understand me and give me a hug every so often, it asks us to behave in the same way towards other people.

372
00:40:47,210 --> 00:40:59,106
So that whole business of interrelationship at work, and especially where there's difficulty with colleagues, these for us are real points of growth.

373
00:41:00,628 --> 00:41:04,434
Another bloody opportunity for growth, as somebody said.

374
00:41:07,818 --> 00:41:10,483
To look upon things positively.

375
00:41:10,463 --> 00:41:40,335
to see these other people who are absolutely awful as our teachers that's the attitude we ought to have then of course there's that constant effort to bring us back into the present moment some of you might know Thich Nhat Hanh and Plum Village and one of the little techniques they use there is they have somebody who randomly rings a bell every so often

376
00:41:40,771 --> 00:41:44,014
And when the bell goes, you have to stop.

377
00:41:44,255 --> 00:41:46,498
Whatever you're doing, you just stop.

378
00:41:46,518 --> 00:41:49,181
And then you wait for the third bell, and then you can carry on.

379
00:41:50,222 --> 00:41:52,565
And they even do that with telephones.

380
00:41:53,246 --> 00:41:58,251
Now, you see, most of us work around telephones or have a telephone at home, you see.

381
00:41:58,291 --> 00:42:03,117
So when a telephone goes, normally we launch ourselves towards it, you see.

382
00:42:03,097 --> 00:42:07,123
So ask yourself, most people will hang on for three or four rings, you see.

383
00:42:07,503 --> 00:42:10,027
And it's a case of acknowledging it.

384
00:42:10,106 --> 00:42:16,556
So if you're doing a piece of work, you see, it's very confusing, at least for males, to have to do two or three things at once.

385
00:42:16,916 --> 00:42:30,014
So it's a case of seeing where you are, acknowledging the phone call, and then just that moment, you see, just that moment of clarification, of clearing the mind, stopping,

386
00:42:29,994 --> 00:42:56,981
and then so that when you answer the phone you've actually given yourself to the whole phone to the phone call so the half the mind isn't still doing your work half the mind isn't still over there you're actually dedicating this time to the phone call you see and then of course when you put the phone down the same thing that's that moment of reflection as to what has passed anything that needs to be done from that phone call whatever and then you know a return back to the work you're doing

387
00:42:56,961 --> 00:43:06,438
a moment of stopping, a recognition, because you've left it mindfully, it's so much easier to remember where you were at, and off you go.

388
00:43:06,777 --> 00:43:16,675
Now, by doing that, you see, you stop this rollercoaster, this rollercoaster of how emotions gather during the day like a storm, you know.

389
00:43:18,123 --> 00:43:23,889
even simple occasions where people have said something which upset you a little bit, you see.

390
00:43:24,188 --> 00:43:31,317
So, you've all been through this, you know, where there's been that little irritation, but you've sort of palmed it aside.

391
00:43:31,396 --> 00:43:32,838
It's just the way they are, you know.

392
00:43:34,300 --> 00:43:37,202
But it's not being dealt with, and it's a little suppression.

393
00:43:37,222 --> 00:43:47,134
And then just when the mind relaxes and you're having a cup of tea or something, you know, how dare you, you know, all that sort of stuff, and you get into this, you know, telling them exactly what you feel and that sort of stuff.

394
00:43:47,114 --> 00:43:55,690
And then, of course, it builds up and, you know, by evening you're sort of hanging them and ripping them apart and then you have to take an aspirin.

395
00:43:55,855 --> 00:44:02,306
So it's a case of watching that, being very clear as to when that happens to actually stop.

396
00:44:02,827 --> 00:44:10,161
And that's where this meditation we're doing has an immediate role to play in our everyday life.

397
00:44:10,541 --> 00:44:11,563
Because that's what we're learning.

398
00:44:11,603 --> 00:44:19,297
We're learning that as soon as I feel any sense of irritation, immediately there's that alarm bell goes and I'm with it.

399
00:44:19,277 --> 00:44:21,141
I don't join it, I don't get into it.

400
00:44:21,201 --> 00:44:24,306
There is irritation or there's anxiety.

401
00:44:24,326 --> 00:44:28,012
As soon as it's there, the alarm bell should go and I should be awake to it.

402
00:44:30,755 --> 00:44:31,818
It only takes a second.

403
00:44:32,177 --> 00:44:41,353
And then to make sure that there's a right attitude and a right understanding from which you're acting from and not from this negativity.

404
00:44:42,581 --> 00:44:45,768
Otherwise, you just get hijacked, don't you?

405
00:44:45,788 --> 00:44:49,135
You just find yourself being angry, being anxious, you see.

406
00:44:50,056 --> 00:44:59,376
So if we take the workplace as a place to train spiritually, you can see it's got massive potential, massive potential, you see.

407
00:45:02,039 --> 00:45:12,650
And then, you know, when you finish work and you come home, you see, that evening meditation really is very important because that's the point where you allow the day to come up.

408
00:45:12,710 --> 00:45:16,155
So at the end of each sitting, you see, I ask people to reflect.

409
00:45:16,876 --> 00:45:17,998
So what are we reflecting on?

410
00:45:18,018 --> 00:45:24,385
We're reflecting upon how skillful we've been through this past three-quarters of an hour, an hour, you see.

411
00:45:24,364 --> 00:45:33,438
And by bringing that reflection up and thinking about it, and then we can see where we've gone wrong, then, you know, we talk to ourselves.

412
00:45:33,679 --> 00:45:38,266
We talk to ourselves in a way that's going to guide us in the proper direction in our meditation.

413
00:45:38,708 --> 00:45:42,333
So it's exactly the same in daily life and at work.

414
00:45:42,813 --> 00:45:50,405
So you come back in the evening and you look back and you think, oh, you know, I did this and I did that and I shouldn't have done this and I shouldn't have done that.

415
00:45:50,385 --> 00:46:00,681
And then one reflects upon it, makes a little determination, and makes that very firm determination that when a similar occasion arises, you know, that you'll be right there on the ball.

416
00:46:02,023 --> 00:46:06,471
Now, on the other side, remember, you have to balance that with congratulating ourselves.

417
00:46:06,451 --> 00:46:18,103
If you're always concerned about the negative, then you never get the joy of having succeeded, of having been successful in some sort of spiritual training.

418
00:46:18,724 --> 00:46:27,534
So when you look back on the day and you've had a difficult situation and you know that you've handled it fairly well, then we ought to say, well, that was good.

419
00:46:27,554 --> 00:46:30,518
A little pat on the head, things like that.

420
00:46:31,695 --> 00:46:32,056
A cake.

421
00:46:33,237 --> 00:46:33,878
Give yourself a cake.

422
00:46:36,681 --> 00:46:40,144
These are the times that we ought to give ourselves little Phillips, you see.

423
00:46:40,445 --> 00:46:42,226
You shouldn't eat cake just because you want to eat a cake.

424
00:46:42,547 --> 00:46:43,628
You should eat cake to celebrate.

425
00:46:45,371 --> 00:46:50,596
Now, if you think about only eating a cake to celebrate, by the end of the day, you've always found something to celebrate.

426
00:46:50,635 --> 00:46:53,498
There's no problem with that at all.

427
00:46:54,599 --> 00:47:00,927
It's a case of getting our attitude right and trying to balance the books.

428
00:47:02,206 --> 00:47:11,597
And in that way, I think, over a period of time, a sort of real balance comes to your life, a sense of purpose, meaningfulness.

429
00:47:12,079 --> 00:47:13,460
And that's really what we want, isn't it?

430
00:47:13,501 --> 00:47:16,023
Sort of a meaningfulness, something that's meaningful.

431
00:47:17,005 --> 00:47:23,673
And paradoxically, we get most meaning when we do things for others.

432
00:47:24,936 --> 00:47:27,940
Compassion, love, sympathetic joy.

433
00:47:29,161 --> 00:47:37,592
Now, when you do that, you see, when you actually do things for others, there's a natural comeback in the heart of feeling joyful.

434
00:47:37,693 --> 00:47:39,534
So you're joyful for somebody else's joy.

435
00:47:40,235 --> 00:47:42,898
You're joyful that you've been able to help somebody in distress.

436
00:47:43,860 --> 00:47:46,923
And you're joyful with friendship.

437
00:47:47,264 --> 00:47:49,306
That's a natural thing, you see.

438
00:47:49,286 --> 00:47:55,737
And that doesn't mean to say that you can't do it for yourself, but you do it for yourself for the right reasons.

439
00:47:55,757 --> 00:48:01,605
But in this case of doing it for others, you see, when we have those beautiful states, that's what Buddhism means by punya.

440
00:48:01,724 --> 00:48:02,646
Punya means merit.

441
00:48:03,507 --> 00:48:07,614
So it becomes vulgarized when you think of merit as some sort of piggy bank, you know.

442
00:48:08,034 --> 00:48:10,858
And when you die, you go to heaven because you've been so good, you see.

443
00:48:11,380 --> 00:48:13,101
That may very well be true.

444
00:48:13,322 --> 00:48:17,809
I mean, you know, there is karmic consequences through time.

445
00:48:17,789 --> 00:48:24,876
which has its original effect in the past, the original cause in the past.

446
00:48:25,657 --> 00:48:37,853
But when we do something which is wholesome and good, the feeling of joy that we get, the feeling of contentment, the feeling of well-being that we have, that is our punya.

447
00:48:38,632 --> 00:48:41,637
That's the merit we have.

448
00:48:43,304 --> 00:48:52,755
You can see now the connection between the process of awakening and the process of good conduct.

449
00:48:53,836 --> 00:48:55,559
You can't have the one without the other.

450
00:48:56,239 --> 00:48:57,460
They come in tandem.

451
00:48:59,344 --> 00:49:02,987
You do get this understanding in Buddhism sometimes that there are two types.

452
00:49:03,047 --> 00:49:11,217
There's one type about karma and creating good in order to get a good rebirth and off and on and then sometime in the future you might go for the enlightenment.

453
00:49:11,197 --> 00:49:17,547
But actually, the one is completely enveloped in the other.

454
00:49:18,606 --> 00:49:26,376
It's a case of understanding that, fine, we can sit and we can devote our lives just to pure meditation.

455
00:49:26,496 --> 00:49:30,481
We can become a hermit and sit in a cave, and surely that's one way.

456
00:49:30,501 --> 00:49:31,983
I mean, that's the Buddha's way, yeah?

457
00:49:32,643 --> 00:49:42,797
I mean, there's a lovely bit in the scripture where some people, some of the monks, go to these various high-standing monks and ask them, you know, what's the path?

458
00:49:42,856 --> 00:49:44,478
What's the path to awakening?

459
00:49:44,458 --> 00:49:46,461
And they split into two main types.

460
00:49:46,501 --> 00:49:52,829
There's the one type led by the great venerable Kasapa, who's a big forest monk, hard on the rule and the Vinaya.

461
00:49:53,409 --> 00:49:59,858
And he says, look, you've got to keep the rules absolutely perfectly, and you've got to sit, meditate, meditate.

462
00:50:00,480 --> 00:50:07,228
And then they go to this other side, which is more Sariputta, and he says, no, you've got to understand the Dharma, you've got to learn the Dharma, and you've got to meditate.

463
00:50:07,869 --> 00:50:10,972
So for that side, the rules don't take primacy.

464
00:50:11,222 --> 00:50:14,786
And so after that they went to the Buddha and said, well, we asked these people and they said this.

465
00:50:14,927 --> 00:50:17,028
And the Buddha says, no, that's all well and good.

466
00:50:17,210 --> 00:50:21,313
Everybody teaches you the way by which they themselves came.

467
00:50:21,954 --> 00:50:24,297
And they said, well, you know, what would you ask us to do?

468
00:50:24,396 --> 00:50:27,099
He says, oh, meditate, meditate, meditate.

469
00:50:28,561 --> 00:50:30,523
So it's pretty direct, you see.

470
00:50:30,543 --> 00:50:37,532
So sure, there are some of us, some human beings, who are drawn to that path, you see.

471
00:50:37,552 --> 00:50:40,335
Drawn to the path of just pure meditation.

472
00:50:40,315 --> 00:50:43,057
But for most of us, there is this path of action.

473
00:50:43,438 --> 00:50:47,461
And that's the way most of us go, I would have thought.

474
00:50:48,643 --> 00:50:50,184
So we've got to make that the path.

475
00:50:50,304 --> 00:50:54,168
We've got to make what we do the path to our own awakening.

476
00:50:54,268 --> 00:50:56,570
If we don't, then we miss out on a chance.

477
00:50:56,690 --> 00:51:06,659
If we think that we're only working spiritually when we come on a weekend retreat or when we're doing meditation in the morning and evening, then a whole chunk of our lives is wasted.

478
00:51:06,757 --> 00:51:15,757
But when you actually turn to your work and see it as the vehicle, as your major vehicle, because heavens, it's the best eight hours of your day, you know, going into work.

479
00:51:16,318 --> 00:51:24,074
So when you see that as your major vehicle, then, of course, that's where your whole effort goes into making sure that vehicle's working for you.

480
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:26,923
And that's the importance of right livelihood.

481
00:51:27,324 --> 00:51:28,706
And it's right there on the path, you see.

482
00:51:29,307 --> 00:51:29,789
Number five.

483
00:51:30,530 --> 00:51:31,271
It is number five.

484
00:51:31,431 --> 00:51:32,072
Right livelihood.

485
00:51:33,356 --> 00:51:41,170
So, once we understand that, once we understand the importance of right livelihood,

486
00:51:41,150 --> 00:51:44,034
then we need to reflect upon it.

487
00:51:45,255 --> 00:52:08,472
And keeping a diary, a spiritual diary, can be very helpful, at least to sort of set us off, to start us going, where at the end of the day you write up what it is that you've done, and what you've learned from the day, and then your little aditan, your little determination,

488
00:52:08,452 --> 00:52:10,757
and then in the morning to repeat that determination.

489
00:52:11,016 --> 00:52:25,701
So when we come to see that, you see, the split that a lot of people make between the monastic life and the lay life, it doesn't appertain, you see.

490
00:52:25,721 --> 00:52:26,442
It doesn't appertain.

491
00:52:27,063 --> 00:52:27,684
It doesn't appertain.

492
00:52:28,786 --> 00:52:35,135
The only, shall we say, plus, you might say, of a monastic life is that, of course...

493
00:52:35,115 --> 00:52:45,614
generally speaking, not always true, your companions tend to be of the same ilk, of the same interest, and they're actually supportive of your effort as you are of theirs.

494
00:52:46,576 --> 00:52:58,677
The problem with living in our society, which is all over the place spiritually, is that, of course, you often work with people whose intentions are quite the opposite.

495
00:53:00,175 --> 00:53:22,315
In a more homogenous society, say in a Christian society, say in the Middle Ages, or even right up to, say, the 18th century before our own Enlightenment, or in present-day Muslim societies, they're probably the best examples, where you have a whole society which is centred upon a particular vision, upon a particular understanding.

496
00:53:22,335 --> 00:53:26,199
I suppose you could say the same of places like Japan or Thailand,

497
00:53:26,179 --> 00:53:32,471
then at least you're working with people of similar understandings who, well, Burma, yeah, Burma.

498
00:53:33,452 --> 00:53:40,425
People who have similar understandings, so you can appeal to people at that level of understanding about the spiritual life.

499
00:53:41,748 --> 00:53:47,378
In the West, that's very difficult because many people don't have that at all on the agenda.

500
00:53:47,358 --> 00:54:02,195
So in that way, that good companionship is the whole of our livelihood, then yes, there can be that draw of having to work with people who are not specifically supporting the way that you want to work.

501
00:54:02,856 --> 00:54:11,045
But even so, if we look at that in a more positive way, rather than see it as a negative thing, then we can make that work for us too.

502
00:54:11,505 --> 00:54:16,891
Working with people who are negative towards what we're trying to do.

503
00:54:19,184 --> 00:54:27,697
So I hope I've convinced you, without any shadow of a doubt, that the path to full awakening lies in the very work you're doing.

504
00:54:28,958 --> 00:54:29,721
Just like the biscuit.

505
00:54:32,204 --> 00:54:34,467
Yes, so any questions arising from that?

506
00:54:35,449 --> 00:54:42,981
Well, comments about your angry old lady, when you dealt with her, was the anger the only successful one?

507
00:54:43,001 --> 00:54:45,224
All four of them.

508
00:54:46,960 --> 00:54:50,766
Yeah, to deal with somebody with anger.

509
00:54:54,231 --> 00:54:59,739
I struggled with this myself over this business of Iraq.

510
00:54:59,760 --> 00:55:05,889
And my essay on the subject, which of course you can all read, is on the website.

511
00:55:05,909 --> 00:55:11,077
And one of the things that helped me was to make a distinction between force and violence.

512
00:55:12,577 --> 00:55:16,442
When something is wrong, one has to use force to put it right.

513
00:55:17,202 --> 00:55:18,905
So, for instance, we have a police force.

514
00:55:18,945 --> 00:55:20,007
We don't have a police violence.

515
00:55:20,827 --> 00:55:22,369
We don't.

516
00:55:22,389 --> 00:55:30,960
And we expect the police to use appropriate means to stop violence, not inappropriate means.

517
00:55:31,221 --> 00:55:34,846
And that, of course, is a fine judgment, but it's to do really with attitude.

518
00:55:35,427 --> 00:55:41,875
So I think in my case with the old lady...

519
00:55:41,855 --> 00:55:53,891
I think I might have been slightly more, shall we say, appealing to her, you know, and sort of sat by her and said, do you realise that since you've come here, you've done nothing but grumble?

520
00:55:53,911 --> 00:55:59,719
Do you realise that all you're doing is creating this very deep, unhealthy feeling within your own heart?

521
00:55:59,760 --> 00:56:03,846
You see, I could have taken her into my confidence, as it were, gently.

522
00:56:03,826 --> 00:56:09,396
As it was, I just plastered her with this little spike of anger.

523
00:56:09,856 --> 00:56:14,083
And of course, fine, fine, she didn't grumble, but I'm sure she was still grumbling.

524
00:56:14,664 --> 00:56:16,188
I mean, it was still in her heart.

525
00:56:16,648 --> 00:56:21,777
So I don't think it achieved a certain, she would say, silence.

526
00:56:23,902 --> 00:56:24,061
LAUGHTER

527
00:56:24,920 --> 00:56:37,335
But unfortunately, the occasion never arose for us to re-establish a warm relationship that had existed when I was being all compassionate and holding, you see.

528
00:56:37,815 --> 00:56:42,242
So in a sense, I don't think it was particularly skillful.

529
00:56:45,445 --> 00:56:49,431
It's one of those moot points that comes from justifiable anger.

530
00:56:49,510 --> 00:56:51,432
That's very difficult in...

531
00:56:52,038 --> 00:56:55,101
in Buddhist understanding, to justify anger as such.

532
00:56:55,902 --> 00:57:00,208
I mean, one can simulate anger, like you might do sometimes with a child.

533
00:57:00,447 --> 00:57:05,494
You can simulate anger and get what you want, but even that can have a...

534
00:57:05,514 --> 00:57:08,376
I mean, the child still receives it as anger, even if you don't feel it.

535
00:57:08,637 --> 00:57:13,322
So it always has some sort of backlash on it.

536
00:57:13,463 --> 00:57:16,527
You might have caught that program, Supernanny,

537
00:57:16,507 --> 00:57:17,168
Have you seen that?

538
00:57:17,768 --> 00:57:18,349
Did you see some of that?

539
00:57:18,610 --> 00:57:19,592
Well, I was very...

540
00:57:19,851 --> 00:57:20,853
I wish I'd have seen all of those.

541
00:57:20,873 --> 00:57:21,916
I thought they were fantastic.

542
00:57:21,996 --> 00:57:22,876
But I only saw the one.

543
00:57:23,597 --> 00:57:27,103
And it was this family where the kids were just ruling the roost.

544
00:57:27,164 --> 00:57:28,025
There were four kiddies.

545
00:57:28,465 --> 00:57:29,467
Absolutely amazing.

546
00:57:29,487 --> 00:57:33,353
And this poor mother was just... She just didn't know how to handle them.

547
00:57:33,875 --> 00:57:36,458
And I thought the little girl was especially wonderful.

548
00:57:36,918 --> 00:57:39,182
And such a lively little personality.

549
00:57:39,202 --> 00:57:40,405
She was about six.

550
00:57:40,385 --> 00:57:42,931
And she wouldn't go to bed.

551
00:57:42,971 --> 00:57:44,514
She had to get up.

552
00:57:44,534 --> 00:57:48,222
And the advice was not to communicate.

553
00:57:48,322 --> 00:57:53,936
Now, she was coming down to communicate, but to just gently take her by the hand and put her back in the bed, you see.

554
00:57:54,456 --> 00:57:56,300
And it was just so funny listening to her comments.

555
00:57:56,320 --> 00:57:57,563
You know, I don't want to go to bed.

556
00:57:57,603 --> 00:57:59,288
I'm fed up with it.

557
00:57:59,268 --> 00:58:01,815
But it was the father who was doing it.

558
00:58:02,237 --> 00:58:06,789
And as soon as she was down, he just gently took her hand and took her all the way upstairs and put her back to bed, you see.

559
00:58:07,150 --> 00:58:08,255
Thirteen times it took.

560
00:58:08,596 --> 00:58:11,083
But after that, it completely stopped, you see.

561
00:58:11,282 --> 00:58:22,253
And it's that sort of, that gentle way, that gentle insistence which gets the right response, you see.

562
00:58:22,753 --> 00:58:33,224
So if he'd have done that angrily, then of course it would have layered onto the whole situation, the anger, and it would have brought up in her anger and all that awful feeling comes up.

563
00:58:33,244 --> 00:58:40,411
And of course, that quality of patience, you know, the Buddha calls it the highest form of ascetic practice.

564
00:58:40,780 --> 00:58:41,521
But it is, isn't it?

565
00:58:42,001 --> 00:58:47,706
I say, you know, it really is ascetic to have to stand there and take the punishment, as it were.

566
00:58:49,088 --> 00:58:51,690
So, yeah.

567
00:58:51,710 --> 00:58:57,534
Are there any other questions that arise from Ripe Livelihood?

568
00:59:00,197 --> 00:59:01,298
Yeah?

569
00:59:01,398 --> 00:59:10,246
I think with the tiff not done, taking it when you stop, you actually breathe three times every time the bell rings, or when you phone,

570
00:59:10,413 --> 00:59:21,925
Yeah, yeah, whatever, yes, whatever, whatever.

571
00:59:22,527 --> 00:59:26,177
All right, all right.

572
00:59:30,376 --> 00:59:41,469
That business of stopping, of course, you can, especially if you're doing something on a machine or like a computer, you know, well, you're supposed to stop anyway, aren't you, after 40 minutes or something, I believe, yeah?

573
00:59:41,489 --> 00:59:42,170
By law, isn't it?

574
00:59:42,871 --> 00:59:43,152
Correct?

575
00:59:43,492 --> 00:59:43,913
Sort of.

576
00:59:43,972 --> 00:59:44,614
You're supposed to.

577
00:59:44,813 --> 00:59:45,554
Okay.

578
00:59:45,574 --> 00:59:53,043
So, you know, if you put your alarm clock on, your little watch alarm, you see, I mean, I do it when I'm working because you just get so absorbed in the machine.

579
00:59:53,103 --> 00:59:54,306
Time just passes.

580
00:59:55,047 --> 00:59:57,750
And every time that bell goes, you know, just to give yourself a break.

